{{Buddhism}}
In [[Buddhist studies]], particularly East Asian Buddhist studies, '''post-canonical Buddhist texts''', '''Buddhist apocrypha''' or '''Spurious Sutras and Sastras''' designate texts that are not accepted as canonical by some historical Buddhist schools or communities who referred to a [[Tripitaka|canon]]. The term is principally applied to texts that purport to represent Buddhist teaching translated from Indian texts, but were written in East Asia.{{sfn|Muller|1998|p=63}}<ref name="李学竹">李学竹. (author tr to English: Li Xuezhu).  中国梵文贝叶概况. (title tr to English: The State of Sanskrit Language Palm Leaf Manuscripts in China). 中国藏学 (journal title tr to English: China Tibetan Studies), 2010年第1期增刊 （总90期）， pp 55-56 (describes discovery of possibly only extant Sanskrit language manuscript of Śūraṅgama Sūtra in Nanyang Henan China, long speculated to be Buddhist apocrypha by some scholars). [https://wenku.baidu.com/view/510144bef111f18582d05a44.html](in Chinese)</ref>

== Examples ==
* ''[[Innumerable Meanings Sutra]]''
* ''Sutra of the Original Acts which Adorn the Bodhisattvas'' (菩薩本業瓔珞經, ''P'u-sa ying-lo pen-yeh ching''){{sfn|Muller|1998|pp=68–9}}
* ''Sutra of Adamantine Absorption'' (金剛三昧經, ''Kŭmgang sammaegyŏng''){{sfn|Muller|1998|p=69}}
* ''Sutra on the Conversion of the Barbarians'' (老子化胡經,  ''Lao-tzu Hua-hu ching''){{sfn|Muller|1998|p=64}}

