{{EngvarB|date=February 2015}} {{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}} {{Infobox Organization |name = Southeast Asian Fisheries Development Center |abbreviation = SEAFDEC |image = SEAFDEC logo.jpg |caption = |map = |msize = |mcaption = |mission = (mandate) to develop and manage the fisheries potential of the region by rational utilisation of the resources for providing food security and safety for people and alleviating poverty through transfer of new technologies, research and information dissemination activities |formation = 1967 |type = intergovernmental organisation |status = |purpose = research, transfer of technologies, and information dissemination activities |headquarters = Bangkok, Thailand |location = Bangkok, Thailand |region_served = ASEAN, Japan |membership = |language = |leader_title = |leader_name = |main_organ = |parent_organization = |affiliations = |num_staff = |num_volunteers = |budget = |website = {{URL|http://www.seafdec.org}} {{URL|http://www.seafdec.or.id}} |remarks = }}
The '''Southeast Asian Fisheries Development Center''' (SEAFDEC) is an autonomous [[Intergovernmental organisation|intergovernmental]] body established as a regional treaty organisation in 1967 to promote [[fisheries]] development in Southeast Asia. SEAFDEC aims specifically to develop the fishery potentials in the region through training, research and information services to improve the food supply by rational utilisation and development of the fisheries resources. Its services cover the broad areas of fishing gear technology, marine engineering, fishing ground surveys and stock assessment, post-harvest technology as well as development and improvement of aquaculture techniques. SEAFDEC is currently made up of 11 Member Countries, namely [[Brunei]] Darussalam, [[Cambodia]], [[Indonesia]], [[Japan]], [[Laos|Lao]] PDR, [[Malaysia]], [[Myanmar]], the [[Philippines]], [[Singapore]], [[Thailand]] and [[Vietnam]], and has the Council of Directors, composed of nominees from Member Countries, as policy-making body to provide directives and guidance on activities of the Center.
<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:Secbuild.jpg]] --> The Center has a Secretariat as its administrative arm, and four technical Departments, namely the Training Department (TD)<ref>[http://www.seafdec.or.th SEAFDEC training]</ref> in Thailand, the Marine Fisheries Research Department (MFRD)<ref>[http://www.fishsafetyinfo.com SEAFDEC network]</ref> in Singapore, the Aquaculture Department (AQD)<ref>[http://www.seafdec.org.ph SEAFDEC Aquaculture Department]</ref> in the Philippines, and the Marine Fishery Resources Development and Management Department (MFRDMD)<ref>[http://www.seafdec.org.my SEAFDEC in Malaysia]</ref> in Malaysia, Inland Fishery Resources Development and Management Department (IFRDMD) <ref>[http://www.seafdec.or.id SEAFDEC in Indonesian]</ref> in Indonesian
The chief administrator of SEAFDEC is the Secretary-General (Dr.Chumnarn Pongsri) whose various responsibilities are directed towards the unification of the activities of the four Departments. In ensuring effective implementation of SEAFDEC program of activities in close co-ordination with the Member Countries, each country also nominates a National Coordinator to co-ordinate issues and activities with SEAFDEC and within the country as well.
